Lanys <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iwanthewicca>IwanTheWicca</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 105<br> <font color=#333333>(11/21/02 4:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=780.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  The reason for re-modeling pets, in my opinion.</span><hr size=1> The Fire pet was our best soloing pet post 39 (disregarding situational times when another pet is better) and verant wanted to make it more appealing for us to group, so the pet would not be tanking.<br>
<br>
With a Damage Shield of 47+ if Voc. was the same old kind of pet, it would allow us to solo for pretty much our entire careers with far greater ease than we currently do. It's the same thinking which has resulted in our 61+ pets being very very strong at offence, but worse than the Epic at defence.<br>
<br>
The only thing wrong with the Fire pet is that Verant didn't come along and specifically tell us than Fire was becoming a group-only pet, not a solo pet. The Game totally shifted with Kunark as it has again with PoP. We've seen the decomation of our nuking capabilities, their restoration, the gimping of our pets and the rise and fall of the mod-rod vending machine.<br>
<br>
In the same way that the pet uses the caster's level to determine their resist of certain spells along with the caster or the pet's resist levels, the same should be done for their casting offensive capabilities. As a 55 Elementalist, when my 49 Fire pet casts upon a Seafury Cyclopse, it should have the same level advantage as I, making them far more easy to land spells on mobs. They have done the same with 61+ melee and pets, making them Lvl 60. Why not the same with spells?<br>
<br>
Mages have always been totally inept at cold spells, bar the Water's process. I could live without 52/58/63 Fire getting cold nukes, but I would love to see the line re-worked.<br>
<br>
The demise of any AoE nukes/cancel magic spells the Fire pet gets has been repeated often. I would love to see the addition of...<br>
<br>
Inferno Shock: 250 DD - Lvl 29<br>
Enticement of Flame: 360 DD Lure &lt;higher likelyhood of hitting mobs&gt; - Lvl 44<br>
Lightning Shock: 405 DD - Lvl 39<br>
O'Keil's FLockering Flame: 5HP DS &lt;stacks&gt; - Level 34<br>
<br>
These are hardly high octane Nukes for the level you will be using the pet.<br>
<br>
Also, FireElementalAura and O'Keil's would result in a 52 DS for the 52 Fire, 55 DS for the 58 and a 67 DS for the 63 Fire pet. WHy have them? The pet has such a minimal amount of HP that it'll get torn through in seconds anyway, why not let it do some damage with its last breaths?<br>
<br>
In short, the 52+ Fire pets aren't rubbish, they are more specialised than before, but their usefulness odes need to be upgraded. I'd love to see a return to the 49 style pet, but it's not going to happen.<br>
<br>
Also, fire pets don't have the insta-cast the way their 49 predecessors did, so anyt esting where it's beign beat on will not be a true representation of its damage potential. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iblisthemage>IblisTheMage</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 178<br> <font color=#333333>(11/22/02 9:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=780.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.decara.com/eq/Federico6060.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The reason for re-modeling pets, in my opinion.</span><hr size=1> I used the air pet for 95% of the situations where I had the choice 50+. The pet is versatile, acting as tank, caster interupter, and mitigator of dammage from the tank by stunning the mob. Water is nice, but it cannot tank an add, and the added damage helps the mage's ego more than the group in many situations =).<br>
